label chapter6:

    # [Scene: Marisol Wetland Reserve | Dawn — the morning after the storm]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Wind sighing through reed beds; distant gulls calling; the low slap of receding waves]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Triumphant strings under quick percussion; a ribbon of brass for warmth]

    scene bg ch6_4001e7_1 at full_bg
    "You breathe in salt and wet earth and for the first time in days the air tastes like possibility instead of dread. The storm left the world rearranged—signs bent, gutters full of silt, the old lamplight"
    "at the edge of town dimmed by sea-spray—but the marsh is stubbornly, outrageously alive. Where last season the water would have clawed past the boardwalk, the restoration mats and planted cordgrass have taken a stand; root"
    "bundles grip the sludge with the same stubbornness you felt as a child learning to tie knots."
    "You feel the co-managed clause like a weight finally lifted from a shoulder you have carried alone. Mayor Rosa kept her word; Lupe holds the cooperative account and the state funds are routed through town oversight."
    "That bureaucratic sentence reads strange next to the smell of mud and sunscreen, but it hums with consequence: materials arriving on time, labor prioritized for local crews, and—vital—community seats at the implementation table. You taste the"
    "relief as sharply as ocean spray."

    scene bg ch6_4001e7_2 at full_bg
    show lupe_kade at left:
        zoom 0.7

    lupe_kade "Maia! You should've seen the berm hold. Jonah's crew scaffolded the northern outfall like it mattered more than their boats—which I think it does."
    hide lupe_kade

    scene bg ch6_4001e7_3 at full_bg
    show maia_rivera at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maia_rivera "They mattered because you asked them to,' you say, lowering your voice but smiling. 'And because you ran the payroll without even blinking."
    show lupe_kade at right:
        zoom 0.7

    lupe_kade "Someone had to keep the numbers from making people cry. But—"
    hide maia_rivera
    hide lupe_kade

    scene bg ch6_4001e7_4 at full_bg
    show lupe_kade at left:
        zoom 0.7

    lupe_kade "—you and Jonah did the hard sell at the meeting. That was the thing that made the town choose to stand with us."
    "Her praise is warm and bright; it sits on your ribs like a steady pulse. Around you, volunteers shout the names of seedlings as if they are blessings; toddlers with rainboots stomp in tidal puddles and"
    "their parents clap at small triumphs. Tomas stands nearby, his back straighter than it has been since the winter, wiping his hands on a towel. When he looks up and catches your eye, something unspools in"
    "the hollow of your chest—an ache of things survived."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Tomas's voice rough with emotion]
    show tomas_rivera at right:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_rivera "I thought I'd be watching the boathouse go, Maia. Was ready to hand the last plank over. But look at this—"
    hide lupe_kade
    hide tomas_rivera

    scene bg ch6_4001e7_5 at full_bg
    show tomas_rivera at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_rivera "—you kept us from losing our anchor."
    show maia_rivera at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maia_rivera "We kept it together,' you correct gently. 'You taught us what to save."
    hide tomas_rivera
    hide maia_rivera

    scene bg ch6_4001e7_6 at full_bg
    show tomas_rivera at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_rivera "And you taught us how to ask for help without losing the asking part."
    "Everything around you accelerates—the work, the laughter, the little ceremonies of mending—and your adrenaline follows like a tide. The arousal that carried you through weeks of meetings blooms now as electric joy. This is not quiet relief; it's a town catching its breath with both hands and starting to run."

    menu:
        "Walk the northern berm with Lupe and point out improvements":
            "You take Lupe's arm and the two of you move along the berm, cataloguing wins aloud—root depth, sediment trapped, volunteer hours—each fact landing like a stone in the river of your relief."
        "Stay with Tomas to help reopen the boathouse ramp":
            "You kneel by the boathouse ramp, hand in the wet grain of wood, and feel the old nail-heads give under your palm. Tomas squeezes your shoulder and the work becomes a blessing you can hold."

    # --- merge ---
    "The chapter continues after either moment with the day's progress toward the harbor reopening."
    # [Scene: The Harbor | Late Afternoon — clean-up, reopening ceremonies]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Staccato claps, a single brass note from a donated trumpet, laughter]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A rising chorus layered with hand drums; heartbeat-like rhythm building]
    hide tomas_rivera

    scene bg ch6_4001e7_7 at full_bg
    "By afternoon the harbor is a festival of elbow grease and small triumphs. You walk the boardwalk and every face is a mapped memory—neighbors you argued with, volunteers who stayed through the worst, the teenagers who"
    "hauled sandbags in the rain. Lupe has already deputized a half-dozen young people to count and record the first disbursements. The cooperative account is not abstract; it's a stack of physical envelopes, stamps of signatures, a"
    "ledger scribbled in block script. You think of every meeting where 'co-managed' felt like an impossible sentence and you let yourself smile at how ordinary it has become."

    scene bg ch6_4001e7_8 at full_bg
    show jonah_kade at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_kade "You look like someone who just closed a deal with the sea."
    show maia_rivera at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maia_rivera "I wish it felt as glamorous as that.' (You step closer; the timber underfoot smells of resin and old salt.) 'It feels more like a long, grudging conversation finally coming to the table."

    jonah_kade "You talk like a lawyer now. Or a sea captain."

    maia_rivera "A bit of both.' (You pull a folded tide map from your Moleskine; your fingers are still muddy.) 'Look—this is last year. See where the channel used to swallow the inlet? This year—' (you tap a line, pointing out newly planted berms and re-routed creeks) '—we kept it from eating the boardwalk."
    "Jonah Kade: (his sea-glass eyes soft) 'Show me again. I like the maps where you get to be right.'"

    maia_rivera "I like the maps where you get to laugh about it later."
    "He reaches without thinking and brushes mud from your hair—more rough habit than ceremony—and your breath forgets the weather for a beat. His hand finds the braid on your Moleskine where a loop of blue cord"
    "dangles, and he tugs it gently, as if checking a string that connects you. The touch is small and ordinary and ferociously important."
    "Jonah Kade: (a softer edge in his voice) 'We didn't do this alone. People showed up because they trust you. And because you trusted them.'"
    "Maia Rivera: (you feel the sentence unspool in the way you exhale) 'I didn't trust easily. I learned. You—' (you hesitate, searching for a word that isn't work or duty) '—you kept showing up, even when I set up more meetings than dinners.'"
    hide jonah_kade
    hide maia_rivera

    scene bg ch6_4001e7_9 at full_bg
    show jonah_kade at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_kade "That's the thing—we're slow at changing how we do it, but once we do, we hold on. Like a good net."
    show maia_rivera at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maia_rivera "And nets are mended."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Behind Jonah, Lupe calls out the first tally of volunteer hours and the crowd whoops. Tomas uncorks a bottle—something cheap and fizzy—and hands you two paper cups.]
    "The harbor feels like an inhale held for decades and finally released. Your chest aches with it."

    menu:
        "Let Jonah wipe the salt from your hair and lean into him":
            "You lean forward and allow the gesture to be more than comfort—his palm at the nape of your neck, warm and real. You both laugh awkwardly and it feels like learning to sail without falling overboard."
        "Hold onto the tide map, keep the moment practical":
            "You tuck the map back into your notebook, smiling but practical. You and Jonah stand shoulder to shoulder, watching the harbor, the intimacy expressed in shared work rather than words."

    # --- merge ---
    "The chapter continues after either moment with the afternoon's reopening ceremony."
    # [Scene: Boathouse Dock Reopening | Golden Hour — ceremony and private reckonings]
    hide jonah_kade
    hide maia_rivera

    scene bg ch6_4001e7_10 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A chorus of cheers, a child's delighted shout; a distant foghorn answering the sky]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Full orchestral swell with choir; percussion quickens to a triumphant pulse]
    "The reopening is both parade and absolution. Tomas stands by the threshold, his fingers trembling on a hammer, his eyes shining as if every memory of the old boathouse had been folded into this single hinge."
    "He does not make speeches; he doesn't need to. When the rope falls and the first little skiff slips into the harbor, the crowd roars. You are swept into hugs—wet, sandy, fierce. Lupe cries openly, mascara"
    "mixing with mud on her cheeks. Jonah squeezes your hand so hard you feel the bones of it."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Tomas's voice breaking]
    show tomas_rivera at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_rivera "You kept us. You kept us all."
    show maia_rivera at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maia_rivera "We kept each other."
    "Elias Wren stands a little apart, hands pocketed, his coat smeared at the hem from helping carry plywood earlier. When he meets your gaze his steel-gray eyes are narrower than usual but not unkind. He crosses"
    "the short distance as the crowd disperses into clusters of conversations that feel like constellations."
    show elias_wren at center:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_wren "You negotiated hard,"
    hide tomas_rivera
    hide maia_rivera
    hide elias_wren

    scene bg ch6_4001e7_11 at full_bg
    show elias_wren at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_wren "I did not foresee the degree of local oversight you'd insist on. But it...works."
    "Maia Rivera: (you feel the edges of that sentence—a compliment and an accusation—like weather at the lip of a storm) 'It had to. People can't be placated with ledger lines when their livelihoods are on the line.'"
    "Elias Wren: (nods; a long beat) 'I have a proposal. Modular pump systems—low-footprint—installed beneath community control, with fish-pass tech integrated. My firm will underwrite the research if the cooperative manages deployment.'"
    "Maia Rivera: (you can sense the room tighten at the name of corporate underwriting, your old reflexes flicker) 'Under community terms, with oversight and guaranteed fish passages. No clauses that allow remote lockouts.'"

    elias_wren "Agreed. We can codify remote access restrictions into the contract. And you will advise on monitoring."
    hide elias_wren

    scene bg ch6_4001e7_12 at full_bg
    show jonah_kade at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_kade "We did this without giving away the bay. If you're on board with that, Maia—"
    hide jonah_kade

    scene bg ch6_4001e7_13 at full_bg
    show jonah_kade at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_kade "—then let's get the specs in writing."
    "The moment tilts like a keel finding balance. Elias offers technology with sincerity and an unusual humility. Jonah offers constancy and a quiet, fierce protectiveness. Lupe has the account and the ledger and the grit to"
    "make sure the tech doesn't become a leash. Tomas has the town's memory and a hand callused in the right places. The community has voice; the state funds have conditions that do not silence it. The"
    "balance is a delicate one but—for the first time in a long time—it feels achievable."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Triumph swells; choir-like voices hold a single, sustaining note as the sun dips lower]
    "Maia Rivera: (you inhale, tasting salt and cedar and the faint ozone of machinery) 'We'll write the clause together. Community seats, terms of access, local labor prioritized, and an independent review board.'"
    "Elias Wren: (a small, honest smile) 'I would expect nothing less.'"
    "The crowd around you starts to fold inward—some to new jobs, some to supper, some to simply watch the light change on the water. Jonah and you find a place on the newly raised boardwalk where"
    "the planks are still warm from the afternoon sun. He hums something tuneless under his breath and you follow that sound like a compass."

    jonah_kade "Promise me something dumb?"
    show maia_rivera at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maia_rivera "Depends how dumb."

    jonah_kade "Promise me you'll keep letting people help you. Not because they need you to be broken, but because the work doubles when it's shared."
    "Maia Rivera: (you feel the old instinct to carry everything alone—that familiar, stubborn guilt—soften like sea glass) 'I promise to let the harbor have a vote.'"
    "Jonah Kade: (he laughs and then kisses the crown of your head, a gesture that is more: a seal for the day's work) 'Good. Because there are a lot more storms to come. But now? Now we have a shoreline that stood.'"
    "Tomas comes to stand beside you both, leaning on his cane and grinning as if he is still slightly stunned by it all. Lupe waves from across the water, her silhouette a little haloed by the"
    "last light. Elias lingers at the edge of the crowd, watching the town reclaim its story. You let the intensity of the day—fear, fury, negotiation, labor—collect and then break like a wave across your stern. Your"
    "guilt, that old ballast, has not disappeared, but it has shifted. You accepted help; you delegated; you trusted a process; you let yourself be held."
    hide jonah_kade
    hide maia_rivera

    scene bg ch6_4001e7_14 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The harbor's hush; an orchestra of crickets begins; a distant, steady thump of a generator hum secured and quiet]
    "Standing on the raised boardwalk, Jonah's rough hand entwined with yours and Lupe's laughter carrying on the wind, you feel the future tack toward something you can recognize. It is not a tidy map with every"
    "hazard removed. It is a living shoreline—messy, negotiated, and fiercely local. It is a promise kept by people who chose to keep it."
    "You close your eyes and for a long moment the world tilts gentle and kind. The tide has shown its teeth and retreated; the marsh held. The boathouse is open; the cooperative has its account; the"
    "technical help will come on terms you wrote with your own hands. Tomas wipes his face and laughs a little, and Jonah squeezes your fingers as if to keep you anchored."
    "You learned that leadership is not an island you stand on alone. It is a bridge you build with others, plank by muddy plank. You let go of the last tightness in your chest and feel"
    "something like forgiveness settle in. The town keeps its voice. The shoreline keeps more of itself. Your guilt unknots into acceptance, and the future—tilted orange and slate—feels like a place you can step into without flinching."

    scene bg ch6_4001e7_15 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle diminuendo into a single sustained, warm chord]

    scene bg ch6_4001e7_16 at full_bg
    "THE END"
